{
  "doc_id": "57792",
  "text": "2 Questionnaires may help to identify severely inactive patients, [CITATION_1] but they largely fail to provide a correct reflection of physical activity across the whole spectrum. Physical activity monitors have become more readily available, and in the European IMI-JU PROactive project (www.PROactiveCOPD) some of these monitors are identified as being valid tools for the assessment of physical activity in patients with COPD. [CITATION_2] The use of activity monitors in primary care has been proposed and validated by others. [CITATION_3] In the future, the use of smart phones containing accelerometers may help in profiling patients at little cost and, importantly, with low time investment.",
